<DOC><DOCNO> AP880630-0297 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0142EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-30 0599</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0626</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government's chief economic forecastinggauge dipped slightly in May, the first setback since January, butanalysts shrugged off the tiny downturn as no threat to prospectsfor the rest of the year.   The Commerce Department reported a 0.1 percent decline lastmonth in the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, primarilyreflecting weakness in the stock market, manufacturing orders andthe labor market. At the same time, the department on Wednesdayrevised upward, from 0.2 percent to 0.5 percent, the gain it hadinitially reported for April.   Economists dismissed the decline, saying growth would continueat least through the remainder of 1988 with no danger of recession.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Securities and Exchange Commission hasasked the Swiss government for help in investigating an alleged $19million insider trading scheme.   SEC Chairman David S. Ruder told the Senate Banking Committee'ssecurities subcommittee Wednesday that his investigators havelearned that Hong Kong businessman Fred C. Lee traded some U.S.securities from Switzerland.   Ruder said the SEC is seeking information from Swissauthorities, and trying to get a freeze on assets held there byLee, who allegedly used insider information garnered by a junioranalyst at Morgan Stanley andamp; Co.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Senate Labor Committee has approvedcompromise legislation to raise the federal minimum wage to $4.55per hour over the next three years.   Floor action on the bill is not expected until after theDemocratic National Convention, which occurs the week of July 18.   Republicans are expected to offer amendments that would cap theincrease at $4 an hour, provide a training wage and exempt allsmall firms from the wage requirement. The current minimum wage is$3.35.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court has ruled that non-unionworkers may withhold financial support from unions representingthem in collective bargaining if some of that money is used foractivities not directly related to the negotiations.   The high court also issued a key civil rights ruling allowingemployees to use statistical evidence to prove their bosses areguilty of illegal discrimination.   The union ruling could deprive many unions of significantportions of their revenue, while the civil rights decision willimpact numerous lawsuits filed by women and members of racialminorities who say they have been treated unfairly.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Environmental Protection Agency hasunveiled massive new draft regulations aimed at upgradingprotection of 2.5 million farm workers from pesticides.   The agency said Wednesday it was unable to estimate how manyworker poisonings would be avoided as a result, because no oneknows how many are occuring now.   Farmers using hired labor, chemical manufacturers and otherswill have to spend an estimated $170 million to comply in the firstyear the regulations are effective, and smaller sums after that,said Louis True, head of program management and support in EPA'spesticide program.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bank of New York Co. has threatened to abandonits hostile $1.4 billion bid for Irving Bank Corp. unless itreceives a favorable court ruling within two days or reaches anamicable settlement with Irving.   Bank of New York stated Wednesday that it submitted a writtenrequest to the New York State Supreme Court for a ruling by Fridayon the validity of Irving's anti-takeover ``poison pill'' andnumerous other pending legal issues.   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady denied the bank wasissuing an ultimatum. Bank of New York's deadline for conditionalmerger approval from the Federal Reserve Board expires on July 9.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>